	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>PACP heads of state call for speeding up of regional EPA process</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In October, Fiji’s Ambassador to the EU revealed that, almost three years after initialling an interim EPA (IEPA), Fiji is now putting in place the domestic mechanisms, legislations and relevant infrastructure needed for the ratification and application of the IEPA. However, he noted Fiji’s continued commitment to negotiating a comprehensive regional EPA with a strong development dimension. This is in line with the statement of Pacific ACP (PACP) ambassadors to Brussels of 18 October calling for a speeding up of the regional EPA process.</p><p>The concern is that unless the regional process towards a comprehensive EPA is accelerated, difficulties could arise from the finalisation of the bilateral IEPA process, which would pre-empt the inclusion of provisions in a regional EPA to which considerable importance is attached by governments of PACP states with only limited interest in trade in goods with the EU.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Fiji Times Online, ‘State works on EPA goal’, 22 October 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=158393" target="_self">http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=158393</a><br/>
Islands Business, ‘Brussels based PACP Ambassadors want EPA negotiations stepped up’, 18 October 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.islandsbusiness.com/news/index_dynamic/containerNameToReplace=MiddleMiddle/focusModuleID=130/focusContentID=21120/tableName=mediaRelease/overideSkinName=newsArticle-full.tpl" target="_self">http://www.islandsbusiness.com/news/index_dynamic/containerNameToReplace...</a><br/>
ICTSD, ‘Riding out the storm: Will the EPAs sink?’, Trade Negotiations Insights, Vol. 9, No. 9, November 2010<br/>

<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/tni/94199/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/tni/94199/</a><br/>
South Centre, ‘EPA contentious issues matrix: key problems and some recommendations’, SC/TDP/AN/EPA/26, June 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.southcentre.org/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=1347%3Aepa-contentious-issues-matrix-key-problems-and-some-recommendations&amp;catid=101%3Aeconomic-partnership-agreements-epas&amp;Itemid=67&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://www.southcentre.org/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article...</a><br/>
Pacific Island Forum Secretariat, ‘Pacific ACP leaders meeting outcomes’, press release (70/10), 4 August 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.pang.org.fj/doc/Pacific_ACP_Leaders%27_Meeting_Outcomes.pdf" target="_self">http://www.pang.org.fj/doc/Pacific_ACP_Leaders%27_Meeting_Outcomes.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The stalled regional comprehensive EPA process is interpreted by some observers as indicative of a loss of momentum within the lead agencies involved in the negotiations. Further delay may lead to further doubts as to the value of the current agreements (with the next round of CAP reform likely to further reduce the value of the traditional sugar-sector trade preferences which underlay Fiji’s initialling of a draft IEPA) and the relevance to smaller ACP states of a restricted regional EPA which does not seem to address their ambitions on labour-market access and other trade-in-services issues.</p><p>Put simply, it seems as though the smaller PACP states which hardly trade with the EU recognise that the type of trade-in-goods agreement initialled by Fiji and PNG is of no real value to them. These governments would rather see trade-in-goods provisions relegated to an optional annex, with greater prominence given to their interests in non trade-in-goods areas. The Solomon Islands’ declared stance of not submitting any market access offers if export taxes and infant industry clause remain on the negotiation table further compounds the difficulties faced. In this context, specific concerns that current IEPA provisions could constrain the policy space for agricultural development will have to be addressed within the EPA process.</p><p>With certain PACP governments keen to see highly beneficial IEPA provisions fully implemented (e.g. the full and secure application of more liberal rules of origin for fisheries products) and with investment flows taking place on a selective basis within the region, pressure for the adoption of bilateral solutions may grow. However, reversion to purely bilateral agreements (as has occurred in the ASEAN region) is likely to leave LDC PACP states dependent on the EBA trade regime, which delivers none of the benefits in non trade-in-goods areas to which these countries aspire.</p><p>In this respect, lessons could be drawn from the Southern Africa region. Here a clear identification of the empirical basis for issues of concern has been established, based on strong inputs from the affected private-sector operators. This has provided a substantive basis for the re-establishment of regional unity backed by high-level political commitments to resolving issues of concern to all regional members. This is improving the prospects for the conclusion of a comprehensive regional EPA in Southern Africa (see <i>Agritrade</i>&nbsp;article, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Thesaurus-labels/Sectors" target="_self">Progress but no imminent signing</a>’, January 2011).</p>
		</div>
		
